\fs36 \cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 The product groups that receive most attention in the realm of DPPs are batteries and those mentioned in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.regenstudio.world/post/what-to-expect-from-the-espr-working-plan-2025-2030"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb2 \ul \ulc5 \strokec5 ESPR Working Plan}}. However, separate regulations around toys, construction materials, plastic packaging, critical raw materials, detergents and vehicles also refer to DPPs as a tool for reporting compliance. Moreover the European Commission in its {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/posts/regen-studio-world_the-single-market-our-european-home-market-activity-7331294733689888768-aT-z?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAAAi-2g0B6sSS5bByFckNB8vzL5D6CVFx_H0"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb2 \ul \ulc5 \strokec5 Single Market Strategy}} mentions DPPs as the envisioned tool for all product related compliance reporting in the future and also refers to DPPs in the '{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://single-market-economy.ec.europa.eu/single-market/simplification_en"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb2 \ul \ulc5 \strokec5 Omnibus IV}}' as a tool for simplifying adhering to market regulations. These insights have led Maximilian Weinhold from Siemens to mention during one of the panels that it is expected that 90% of all products in the EU will be required to use a DPP in the future.\cb1 \
